<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910409-0051</DOCNO><DOCID>910409-0051.</DOCID><HL>   Poling's '90 Compensation   At Ford Declined by 59%</HL><DATE>04/09/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4</SO><CO>   F LABOR</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><NS>LABOR, PERSONNEL ISSUES, TRENDS, MANAGEMENT TECHNIQUES (LAB)</NS><RE>MICHIGAN (MI)</RE><LP>   DEARBORN, Mich. -- Ford Motor Co.'s Harold A. Poling, whotook over as chairman last March, saw his total compensationdrop 59% in 1990 despite the promotion, according to thecompany's proxy statement.   Mr. Poling got his $1.2 million salary in 1990, butreceived no bonuses and exercised no stock options, the proxysaid. He received $2.9 million in total compensation as vicechairman and chief operating officer in 1989.</LP><TEXT>   By contrast, Mr. Poling's predecessor, Donald E. Petersen,earned more than $6.6 million in 1989, including a $1.5million salary, a $1.5 million bonus and $3.5 million fromexercising options.   Ford President Philip E. Benton Jr. had total compensationof $1.1 million in 1990, including $348,750 from exercisingstock options. The previous year, as a Ford executive vicepresident, he had total compensation of $2.1 million.   Despite the drop in compensation, the United Auto Workersunion issued its customary criticism of executive pay levels.&quot;The disparity between the amounts paid to Ford's topmanagers and the wages received by its salaried and hourlyworkers . . . is far too wide and raises deep concerns aboutthe values of Ford's corporate leadership,&quot; union officialssaid in a statement.</TEXT></DOC>